    <section class="consulting-block consulting-block--lead" id="what-i-do" data-label="What I do" aria-labelledby="what-i-do-heading">
      <div class="consulting-block-copy">
        <h2 class="consulting-block-eyebrow" id="what-i-do-heading">What I do</h2>

        <p>Most global health programs run two versions of themselves: the one in the reporting documents, and the one being delivered at the door. The two versions do not always agree, and in most programs no one is responsible for closing the gap between them. Programs end up defending the reporting version, because the reporting version is what gets audited &ndash; even when the field has quietly worked out something better.</p>

        <p>I work between those two versions.</p>

        <p>I read the program as it is actually delivered, render that reading in language the institution can act on, and help the team build the social processes that let field-level knowledge legitimately revise the official frame without breaking the funding model. The methods I draw on most often &ndash; <em>Brokered Design</em> and <em>Brokered Dialogue</em>, developed over the last seven years with Jim Lavery &ndash; are structured ways of brokering insight between stakeholder groups who would not otherwise be able to revise each other&rsquo;s positions.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="consulting-block" id="getting-started" data-label="Getting Started" aria-labelledby="getting-started-heading">
      <div class="consulting-block-copy">
        <h2 class="consulting-block-eyebrow" id="getting-started-heading">Getting Started</h2>

        <p>If you would like to work together, send me a short or long note about the problem you&rsquo;re working on. Email or DM is fine. I&rsquo;ll ask follow-up questions to figure out whether I can be useful before either of us puts time or money down. The more context you share, the better I can dig in beforehand, and the more useful our first call will be.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="consulting-block consulting-arrangement" id="what-to-expect" data-label="Working with me: What to expect" aria-labelledby="what-to-expect-heading">
      <div class="consulting-block-copy">
        <h2 class="consulting-block-eyebrow" id="what-to-expect-heading">Working with me: What to expect</h2>

        <p>Most engagements start with a paid &ldquo;thought sparring&rdquo; conversation: <span class="consulting-price">$350 for a 60&ndash;90 minute call.</span> I send a few prep questions a day or two ahead. The purpose of the call is for me to better understand the situation and figure out the next useful move, while giving you a sense of whether you&rsquo;re <a class="consulting-quiet-link" href="https://stephango.com/in-good-hands">in good hands</a>.</p>

        <p>I only book the call if I&rsquo;m confident I can deliver more than $350 in value to you. If I can&rsquo;t, I&rsquo;ll tell you, and where I can, point you to someone who fits better.</p>

        <p>If $350 is too much, write anyway. Depending on your situation, there&rsquo;s flexibility on rate for early-stage or public-interest work.</p>

        <p>Beyond the first call, scope and rate are discussed and agreed in writing.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="consulting-more-knots" id="recurring-problems-section" aria-labelledby="recurring-problems-heading">
      <div class="consulting-block-copy">
        <h2 class="consulting-block-eyebrow" id="recurring-problems-heading">Recurring problems</h2>

        <p>This work falls into a few recurring shapes. The named problems below are drawn from established consulting literature &ndash; Edgar Schein, Gerald Weinberg, and others &ndash; that names the dysfunctions practitioners actually run into. Each entry pairs the concept with an engagement from my own record.</p>

        <h3 class="consulting-subhead" id="frameworks-subhead">A note on frameworks</h3>

        <p>&ldquo;Wicked problems&rdquo; is a frame for hard problems. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/14494035.2019.1617971">The term has been used too many ways to mean much</a>. Once I&rsquo;ve called a problem wicked, I know it is hard. I do not know what kind of hard, or what to do next.</p>

        <p>Frameworks &ndash; VUCA, wicked, whatever is current &ndash; are useful for talking about problems. They are less useful for working through them. The specifics of any particular program are always more granular than the label that gets applied to it.</p>

        <h3 class="consulting-subhead" id="problem-examples">Examples from past work</h3>

        <h4 class="consulting-knot-name">The presenting problem vs. the real problem.</h4>
        <p class="consulting-knot-attribution"><em>Schein, Humble Consulting (2016).</em></p>

        <p>What the client says they need help with rarely matches what is actually worrying them. The presented version is usually accurate as far as it goes; it is also usually the version that has been approved upward, written into reporting cycles, and rehearsed enough times to sound complete. The real concern tends to surface later, after enough relationship has been built that the client can risk saying it out loud, or after the data the project produces starts to contradict the framing the project was funded under.</p>

        <p><em>Haiti, 2019&ndash;2023.</em> The Carter Center&rsquo;s LF-MDA program in L&eacute;og&acirc;ne and Gressier presented the problem as persistent non-compliance: a roughly 35% residual share of the population that consistently did not participate in annual MDA campaigns. The standard interpretation &ndash; fear of side effects, rumor, religious concerns &ndash; was almost certainly true for some subset, and the program had invested considerably in addressing it. But the co-production interviews surfaced a different pattern: a substantial fraction of the people who satisfied the program&rsquo;s operational definition of non-compliance (i.e., 0 or 1 participation across the prior five rounds) had been willing to participate and had not been reached. The post had run out of pills before they arrived; the team had moved through their neighborhood faster than residents could respond; or canvassing happened during working hours and no one was home to answer the door. The cut, in practice, was disaggregating &ldquo;non-compliance&rdquo; into access-bounded and refusal-bounded sub-types, each requiring different operational adjustments (i.e., stock-flow planning and team routing on one side, motivational communication and trust work on the other).</p>
      </div>
    </section>
